      <h1>Do What You Say You're Going to Do</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">The simplest idea in sales, and the one most people don't actually follow</p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main class="wrap">
    <p>If you asked me to boil down everything I've learned in more than 15 years of healthcare and animal health sales into one sentence, it wouldn't be about a closing technique, a CRM workflow, or a clever way to handle objections. It would be this: do what you say you're going to do.</p>

    <blockquote>It sounds too simple to matter. That's exactly why it works.</blockquote>

    <h2>Why the simple version gets overlooked</h2>
    <p>Sales training tends to focus on the moments that feel high-stakes — the pitch, the negotiation, the close. Those matter, but they're not where most reps actually lose trust. Trust erodes in the small, unglamorous follow-through: the sample you said you'd send, the call-back you promised for Tuesday, the answer you said you'd track down by end of week. None of that shows up in a sales training deck, but all of it shows up in whether a customer believes you.</p>

    <h2>What it looks like in healthcare sales specifically</h2>
    <p>In diagnostics and healthcare sales, the sales cycle is long and the relationships are longer. A veterinary practice or a physician's office isn't deciding whether to trust you based on one great meeting — they're watching, over months and years, whether the small things you commit to actually happen. Did the equipment demo happen on the day you said it would? Did the pricing follow-up actually arrive when promised? Did the issue you said you'd escalate actually get escalated? Every one of those is a tiny test, and every tiny test either builds the account or quietly erodes it.</p>

    <h2>Why it separates reps more than talent does</h2>
    <p>Plenty of sales reps are talented — good at building rapport, good at explaining a product, good in the room. Far fewer are reliably consistent about follow-through, especially once the relationship isn't new anymore and the excitement of the pitch has worn off. That consistency is what actually gets rewarded over time: renewed contracts, recovered competitive accounts, referrals you didn't have to ask for. None of that comes from being the most charismatic person in the meeting. It comes from being the person whose word can be counted on, meeting after meeting, quarter after quarter.</p>

    <h2>It's also just simpler to live by</h2>
    <p>Part of why I've stuck with this principle is that it doesn't require remembering a framework. You don't need to recall a four-step model under pressure — you just need to not say things you don't intend to follow through on, and then follow through on the things you do say. It's a low bar in theory and a surprisingly high one in practice, which is exactly why it's a real differentiator rather than a platitude.</p>

    <h2>Where this shows up beyond sales</h2>
    <p>This isn't just a sales philosophy for me — it's the same instinct behind the businesses I've built outside of my healthcare career. You can read more about <a href="/why-i-build-businesses">why I build businesses</a>, or see the fuller picture of my career on my <a href="/career-journey">career journey</a> page and <a href="/resume">resume</a>.</p>
